<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 7.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3><strong>Creating Responsive and Effective MCH Systems</strong></h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-bullhorn"></i> <strong>7K1.</strong>  Organizational Decision-Making Processes</button>
  <div class="panel">
      <p dir="ltr">Understanding how individual perspectives shape decision-making within health organizations is crucial for effective leadership. This involves:</p>
      <p dir="ltr">Personal influence on professional judgment: Our personal experiences and backgrounds significantly impact how we interpret information and make decisions in professional settings. Research shows that healthcare leaders with direct experience of certain health challenges often prioritize related services more strongly.¹</p>
      <p dir="ltr">Multiple perspectives in organizational strategy: Organizations that incorporate varied viewpoints in strategic planning are more likely to develop comprehensive approaches to complex MCH challenges. Studies indicate that teams with various perspectives  make better decisions 87% of the time.²</p>
      <p dir="ltr">Systemic impact of individual viewpoints: Individual preferences and perspectives can become institutionalized within organizational structures, potentially creating imbalances in service delivery. This &quot;structural embodiment&quot; of perspective requires conscious examination.³</p>
      <p dir="ltr">Background factors in decision-making: Professional training and personal background and  values create unique lenses through which leaders evaluate options and priorities. Awareness of these influences enables more balanced and objective decision-making processes.⁴</p>
      <p dir="ltr">Creating comprehensive decision frameworks that acknowledge these dynamics helps MCH organizations develop more responsive systems that better serve all populations.  </p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book-open-1"></i> <strong>7K2.</strong> Recognize Organizational Influences.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p dir="ltr">Exploring how policies and organizational strategies intersect to influence health outcomes:</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Policy development and implementation: The process of translating policy into practice involves complex interactions between federal guidelines, state implementations, and local adaptations. These multi-level dynamics significantly impact how policies ultimately affect MCH populations.⁵</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Policy-practice relationships: The alignment between policy frameworks and service delivery determines effectiveness. Policies disconnected from frontline realities often fail to achieve intended outcomes for mothers and children.⁶</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Organizational impact assessment: Organizational approaches directly influence health system effectiveness through resource allocation, priority setting, and performance measurement. Regular assessment of these approaches is essential for continuous improvement.⁷</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Strategic leverage points: Identifying key intervention points within complex systems allows for speific improvements with maximum impact. These leverage points often exist at the intersection of policy, funding, and implementation processes.⁸</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Ppolicy contexts: Understanding the  development of MCH policies provides  insights into current challenges and opportunities. Many contemporary differences in outcomes have roots in past policy decisions that require acknowledgment and reconsideration.⁹</p>
    <p dir="ltr">Effective MCH leaders navigate these intersections by developing organizational approaches that align with evidence-based policies while remaining adaptable to community needs and emerging challenges.  </p>
  </div>
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>7K3.</strong>  Factors Influencing Health Outcomes</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Investigating the multiple factors that contribute to health differences:</p>
    <p>Interaction of several factors: Economic and environmental factors interact in complex ways to create differences in health outcomes. For example, housing insecurity often correlates with food access challenges, creating compounded obstacles to maternal and child health.¹⁰</p>
    <p>Systems complexity analysis: Health outcomes emerge from interconnected systems including healthcare, education, housing, transportation, and social services. Understanding these connections is essential for effective interventions.¹¹</p>
    <p>Determinant interconnectedness: Health factors form networks of influence rather than isolated elements. For instance, educational opportunities affect employment, which influences healthcare access, nutritional options, and ultimately maternal and child health outcomes.¹²</p>
    <p>Intervention mapping: Identifying effective interventions requires mapping the complex pathways through which various factors influence health. This process helps prioritize actions with the greatest potential impact across multiple determinants.¹³</p>
    <p>These understandings enable MCH leaders to develop comprehensive approaches that address root causes rather than symptoms, creating sustainable improvements in population health outcomes.</p>
  </div>
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-medkit"></i> <strong>7K4.</strong> Evidence-Based Strategies for Engagement</button>
  <div class="panel">
  <p>Developing strategies to improve participation and effectiveness:</p>
  <p>System improvement approaches: Evidence supports specific strategies for enhancing system responsiveness, including human-centered design, continuous quality improvement, and collaborative governance models. These approaches share a focus on partner engagement and iterative improvement.¹⁴</p>
  <p>Organizational engagement methods: Techniques for strengthening organizational commitment include shared leadership models, clear communication channels, transparent decision-making processes, and meaningful opportunities for staff input. Organizations implementing these methods show higher performance on MCH quality measures.¹⁵</p>
  <p>Participation enhancement: Strategies that successfully increase participation in research and programs include community-based participatory approaches, tailored recruitment methods, addressing practical obstacles (transportation, childcare), and providing meaningful incentives. These approaches have been shown to improve representation of various MCH populations.¹⁶</p>
  <p>Implementation effectiveness: Successful system-wide improvements require attention to implementation science principles, including partner engagement, contextual adaptation, adequate resources, supportive leadership, and ongoing monitoring. MCH programs using implementation frameworks show 3-4 times greater sustainability rates.¹⁷</p>
  <p>By applying these evidence-based strategies, MCH leaders can create systems that meaningfully engage partners at all levels, leading to more effective and responsive services.</p> </div>

  
 
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-pencil-square-o"></i> <strong>7S1.</strong>  Conduct self-assessments.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Develop skills to assess personal and organizational effectiveness:</p>
    <p>Strength/growth area identification: Regular self-assessment using validated tools helps identify both personal strengths and areas for development in creating responsive systems. Methods include 360-degree feedback, reflective practice journals, and competency-based assessments.¹⁸</p>
    <p>Professional development planning: Creating structured plans for ongoing learning that align with identified growth areas ensures continuous improvement in leadership capabilities. Effective plans include specific goals, actionable steps, timelines, and measurement strategies.¹⁹</p>
    <p>Self-reflective practice: Implementing routines for  self-reflection enhances self-awareness and improves decision-making. Techniques include structured reflection exercises, peer coaching conversations, and professional journaling.²⁰</p>
    <p>Performance improvement methodologies: Developing familiarity with improvement frameworks (PDSA cycles, Six Sigma) provides systematic approaches to enhancing both personal and organizational effectiveness in MCH systems.²¹</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>7S2.</strong> Recognize Organizational Strengths.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Identify and support organizational capabilities:</p>
    <p>Team strength assessment: Systematically evaluating the unique strengths and assets within professional teams helps leverage collective capabilities. Methods include appreciative inquiry, skills inventories, and strengths-based team assessments.²²</p>
    <p>Multiple perspective valuation: Understanding how different professional backgrounds and personal experiences contribute to organizational effectiveness helps create more comprehensive approaches. This includes recognizing both clinical and non-clinical expertise as valuable.²³</p>
    <p>Capability leveraging strategies: Developing approaches to maximize organizational strengths involves creating structures that align team member strengths with organizational needs and creating opportunities for cross-functional collaboration.²⁴</p>
    <p>Team potential maximization: Creating strategies that nurture professional growth while honoring existing capabilities ensures sustainable organizational development. This includes mentoring programs, communities of practice, and skill-sharing initiatives.²⁵</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comments-1"></i> <strong>7S3.</strong> Develop Professional Awareness.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Build professional behaviors that support effective leadership:</p>
    <p>Multiple perspective acknowledgment: Developing habits that actively seek and incorporate varied viewpoints in decision-making processes enhances system responsiveness. Techniques include structured decision frameworks that mandate consideration of different perspectives.²⁶</p>
    <p>Decision calibration strategies: Creating approaches to recognize and address potential preferences in professional judgment improves outcomes in MCH systems. Methods include awareness training, decision review processes, and partner involvement from various backgrounds.²⁷</p>
    <p>Objective assessment approaches: Implementing practices that support comprehensive understanding requires frameworks for objective evaluation. This includes using standardized assessment tools, involving multiple evaluators, and separating observation from interpretation.²⁸</p>
    <p>Professional self-regulation: Developing the capacity to recognize and manage emotional responses to challenging situations enables more effective leadership. Techniques include mindfulness practices, peer support systems, and professional coaching.²⁹</p>
  </div>
    
   
 
 
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
 
 
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>7S4.</strong> Adapt Clinical and Public Health Systems.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Modify clinical and public health systems to address specific needs:</p>
    <p>Flexible system design: Developing approaches to organizational structure and process that can be readily adapted to meet emerging needs and changing contexts. This includes modular service designs, rapid-cycle testing, and distributed decision-making authorities.³⁰</p>
    <p>Responsive organizational strategies: Creating strategic planning processes that incorporate regular feedback loops and environmental scanning to ensure ongoing relevance to community needs. Methods include scenario planning, community advisory boards, and dynamic strategic frameworks.³¹</p>
    <p>Adaptive service delivery: Implementing approaches that allow service models to evolve based on changing population needs, emerging evidence, and resource availability. This includes training staff in adaptability, creating modification protocols, and prioritizing core functions over specific methods.³²</p>
    <p>Evolutionary system design: Designing systems with built-in capacity for growth and change through practices such as developmental evaluation, flexible infrastructure, and scalable processes.³³</p>
  </div>
    
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-language"></i> <strong>7S5.</strong> Improve Service Delivery</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Enhance effectiveness in public health and healthcare:</p>
    <p>Service improvement strategy development: Creating comprehensive approaches to enhance service quality, accessibility, and responsiveness. This includes service mapping, gap analysis, and obstacle reduction planning.³⁴</p>
    <p>Evidence-based implementation: Applying research findings and best practices to service delivery while adapting to local contexts. Methods include evidence synthesis, implementation frameworks, and practice-based research.³⁵</p>
    <p>System optimization methods: Developing techniques for ongoing system refinement through performance monitoring, user feedback, and comparative benchmarking. This includes developing meaningful metrics that reflect both process quality and outcomes.³⁶</p>
    <p>Organizational effectiveness design: Creating approaches that increase overall organizational performance through improved coordination, strategic resource allocation, and continuous learning processes.³⁷</p>
  </div>
        <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-share"></i> <strong>7S6.</strong> Incorporate Comprehensive and Responsive Approaches.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Incorporate comprehensive and responsive approaches into programs, research, education, communications, and policies:</p>
    <p>Program-policy integration: Creating aligned approaches that connect programmatic interventions with supportive policy frameworks to maximize impact and sustainability. This includes policy analysis, strategy development for improvement, and policy-program feedback loops.³⁸</p>
    <p>Research integration strategies: Developing comprehensive research approaches that incorporate multiple methods, disciplines, and partner perspectives. Methods include mixed-methods designs, cross-disciplinary teams, and integrated knowledge translation.³⁹</p>
    <p>Cross-domain communication: Designing communication approaches that effectively share information and build understanding across professional domains, sectors, and communities. This includes developing shared terminology, visual communication tools, and targeted messaging.⁴⁰</p>
    <p>Multi-faceted intervention design: Implementing interventions that address multiple aspects of complex MCH challenges simultaneously through coordinated actions across different levels and systems.⁴¹</p>
  </div>
<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>7S7.</strong> Utilize Data-Driven Tools.</button>
  <div class="panel">
	<p>Use data-driven tools and detailed data analysis to identify trends, improve health efforts, and communicate findings in clear, straightforward language:</p>
    <p>Advanced data analysis: Developing  statistical methods, qualitative analysis, geographic information systems, and predictive modeling to extract meaningful insights from complex data sources.⁴²</p>
    <p>Performance evaluation tools: Creating frameworks and instruments for systematic assessment of program and system performance, including balanced scorecards, logic models, and contribution analysis methods.⁴³</p>
    <p>Data-driven decision processes: Implementing structured approaches to incorporate data into strategic and operational decisions, including data review protocols, decision matrices, and evidence hierarchies.⁴⁴</p>
    <p>Impactful communication design: Developing skills in translating complex data into clear, compelling formats that drive action among various partners, including data visualization, narrative methods, and audience-specific presentations.⁴⁵</p>
  </div>
    
  
